pr_review_comment_body:
> On treeherder we tend to avoid the term branch as much as possible because it can lead to confusion. What about
> Missing jobs triggered for result-set {resultset}

I'd like us to move back to using "push" instead of resultset if possible - seeing as the only reason we used resultset was for the multi-repo use-case which we're not using, and may possibly deprecate in the future?

I don't think we need an else block here.

```
if (foo) {
  return bar
} else {
   ...
}
```

is equivalent to:
```
if (foo) {
  return bar
}
...
```

@aronasorman yes sure, I can do that. But what is the `usbdiscover` module you are talking about? Sorry I'm not following you here. 
@indirectlylit It seems that `deviceadmin` is for database backup? Not sure if I can put it there..

I was thinking previously that putting this endpoint to the `content` module under ChannelMetadataViewset, since we only call this in the channel detail page, but may not be a good idea?

It's worth noting that this function will return a generator which is probably not what you actually want.  I would suggest writing an outer function `get_trie_nodes` and renaming this function to `_get_trie_nodes` like the following.


```python
def get_trie_nodes(...):
    return tuple(_get_trie_nodes(...))
```

This will allow all of the various iterators to be lazily evaluated at the very end and cast to a single tuple.

Well, I could adjust this, but it's not possible to have a negative quantity anymore:

        # don't allow quantities to be negative
        if basket.product_quantity(product) + quantity < 0:
            return False, _("Negative quantities are not allwed")
        return True, None

if I use weightsBias(i) = Tensor[T](wb)
followed by wb.set()
storage of weightsBias(i) is also set.

`layer.get_output_for` could also be a function if somebody monkey-patches an instance. This won't be a common use case, but I'm still a bit worried about making the implementation less generic just to cater for deficits in the test framework.
To make it a little more robust, what about either:
```python
if isinstance(layer.get_output_for, (MethodType, FunctionType)):
```
or:
```python
try:
    names, _, _, defaults = getargspec(layer.get_output_for)
except TypeError:
    pass  # if introspection is not possible, skip it
else:
    if defaults is not None:
        accepted_kwargs |= set(names[-len(defaults):])
```

As I noted outside the review: see [C.47](https://github.com/isocpp/CppCoreGuidelines/blob/master/CppCoreGuidelines.md#Rc-order) and [C.48](https://github.com/isocpp/CppCoreGuidelines/blob/master/CppCoreGuidelines.md#Rc-in-class-initializer).

Following those rules you'll get:
```cpp
const size_t resulting_queue_max_size = 20;
rs2::frame_queue syncer_queue;
rs2::frame_queue resulting_queue{ resulting_queue_max_size };
```
Which makes it clear and it is all located in the same place.
Also you can see from this that `syncer_queue` is not initialized to any specific value...

Hmm, perhaps we can add a second fallback for the `en_US.UTF-8` variant which I think is just an alias?  E.g.

```python
try:
  locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, 'en_US.utf8')
except Exception:
  try:
    locale.setlocale(locale.LC_ALL, 'en_US.UTF-8')
  except Exception:
    raise self.skipTest('Environment does not support en_US.utf8/en_US.UTF-8 locale')
```
